# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qt-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:qt-framework/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A **graphical user interface**, or **GUI**, is a form of user interface that allows users to interact with electronic devices through graphical icons and visual indicators such as secondary notation.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In many applications, GUIs are used instead of text-based UIs, which are based on typed command labels or text navigation.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] GUIs were introduced in reaction to the perceived steep learning curve of command-line interfaces (CLIs), which require commands to be typed on a computer keyboard.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The actions in a GUI are usually performed through direct manipulation of the graphical elements.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Beyond computers, GUIs are used in many handheld mobile devices such as MP3 players, portable media players, gaming devices, smartphones and smaller household, office and industrial controls.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Designing the visual composition and temporal behavior of a GUI is an important part of software application programming in the area of human–computer interaction.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Its goal is to enhance the efficiency and ease of use for the underlying logical design of a stored program, a design discipline named *usability*.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Methods of user-centered design are used to ensure that the visual language introduced in the design is well-tailored to the tasks.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The visible graphical interface features of an application are sometimes referred to as *chrome* or *GUI*.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Typically, users interact with information by manipulating visual widgets that allow for interactions appropriate to the kind of data they hold.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The widgets of a well-designed interface are selected to support the actions necessary to achieve the goals of users.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A model–view–controller allows flexible structures in which the interface is independent of and indirectly linked to application functions, so the GUI can be customized easily.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This allows users to select or design a different *skin* or *theme* at will, and eases the designer's work to change the interface as user needs evolve.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Good GUI design relates to users more, and to system architecture less.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Large widgets, such as windows, usually provide a frame or container for the main presentation content such as a web page, email message, or drawing.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Smaller ones usually act as a user-input tool.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A GUI may be designed for the requirements of a vertical market as application-specific GUIs.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Cell phones and handheld game systems also employ application specific touchscreen GUIs.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Newer automobiles use GUIs in their navigation systems and multimedia centers, or navigation multimedia center combinations.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A GUI uses a combination of technologies and devices to provide a platform that users can interact with, for the tasks of gathering and producing information.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A series of elements conforming a visual language have evolved to represent information stored in computers.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This makes it easier for people with few computer skills to work with and use computer software.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The most common combination of such elements in GUIs is the *windows, icons, text fields, canvases, menus, pointer* (WIMP) paradigm, especially in personal computers.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The WIMP style of interaction uses a virtual input device to represent the position of a pointing device's interface, most often a mouse, and presents information organized in windows and represented with icons.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Available commands are compiled together in menus, and actions are performed making gestures with the pointing device.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A window manager facilitates the interactions between windows, applications, and the windowing system.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The windowing system handles hardware devices such as pointing devices, graphics hardware, and positioning of the pointer.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In personal computers, all these elements are modeled through a desktop metaphor to produce a simulation called a desktop environment in which the display represents a desktop, on which documents and folders of documents can be placed.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Window managers and other software combine to simulate the desktop environment with varying degrees of realism.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Entries may appear in a list to make space for text and details, or in a grid for compactness and larger icons with little space underneath for text.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Variations in between exist, such as a list with multiple columns of items and a grid of items with rows of text extending sideways from the icon.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Multi-row and multi-column layouts commonly found on the web are "shelf" and "waterfall".
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The former is found on image search engines, where images appear with a fixed height but variable length, and is typically implemented with the CSS property and parameter `display: inline-block;`.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] A waterfall layout found on Imgur and TweetDeck with fixed width but variable height per item is usually implemented by specifying `column-width:`.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Smaller app mobile devices such as personal digital assistants (PDAs) and smartphones typically use the WIMP elements with different unifying metaphors, due to constraints in space and available input devices.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Applications for which WIMP is not well suited may use newer interaction techniques, collectively termed *post-WIMP* UIs.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] As of 2011, some touchscreen-based operating systems such as Apple's iOS (iPhone) and Android use the class of GUIs named post-WIMP.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] These support styles of interaction using more than one finger in contact with a display, which allows actions such as pinching and rotating, which are unsupported by one pointer and mouse.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] There are also actions performed by programs that affect the GUI.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] For example, there are components like inotify or D-Bus to facilitate communication between computer programs.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Ivan Sutherland developed Sketchpad in 1963, widely held as the first graphical computer-aided design program.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] It used a light pen to create and manipulate objects in engineering drawings in realtime with coordinated graphics.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In the late 1960s, researchers at the Stanford Research Institute, led by Douglas Engelbart, developed the On-Line System (NLS), which used text-based hyperlinks manipulated with a then-new device: the mouse.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Most modern general-purpose GUIs are derived from this system.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The Xerox PARC GUI consisted of graphical elements such as windows, menus, radio buttons, and check boxes.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The concept of icons was later introduced by David Canfield Smith, who had written a thesis on the subject under the guidance of Kay.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The PARC GUI employs a pointing device along with a keyboard.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] These aspects can be emphasized by using the alternative term and acronym for *windows, icons, menus, pointing device* (WIMP).
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This effort culminated in the 1973 Xerox Alto, the first computer with a GUI, though the system never reached commercial production.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The first commercially available computer with a GUI was the 1979 PERQ workstation, manufactured by Three Rivers Computer Corporation.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Its design was heavily influenced by the work at Xerox PARC.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In 1981, Xerox eventually commercialized the ideas from the Alto in the form of a new and enhanced system – the Xerox 8010 Information System – more commonly known as the Xerox Star.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Visi On was released in 1983 for the IBM PC compatible computers, but was never popular due to its high hardware demands.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Nevertheless, it was a crucial influence on the contemporary development of Microsoft Windows.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Apple, Digital Research, IBM and Microsoft used many of Xerox's ideas to develop products, and IBM's Common User Access specifications formed the basis of the GUIs used in Microsoft Windows, IBM OS/2 Presentation Manager, and the Unix Motif toolkit and window manager.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] These ideas evolved to create the interface found in current versions of Microsoft Windows, and in various desktop environments for Unix-like operating systems, such as macOS and Linux.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Thus most current GUIs have largely common idioms.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The early 1980s saw growing interest in GUIs.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The Apple Lisa was released in 1983, but was expensive and commercially unsuccessful.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Individual applications for many platforms presented their own GUI variants.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Despite the GUI's advantages, many reviewers questioned the value of the entire concept, citing hardware limits and problems in finding compatible software.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In 1984, Apple introduced the Macintosh via the "1984" television commercial during Super Bowl XVIII, with allusions to George Orwell's novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The goal of the commercial was to make people think about computers, identifying the user-friendly interface as a personal computer which departed from prior business-oriented systems, and becoming a signature representation of Apple products.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The 1985 Atari ST shipped with the GEM GUI from Digital Research, which was also published for MS-DOS.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The Amiga 1000 was released the same year, though not widely available until 1986, with the Workbench graphical desktop.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This interface ran as a separate task, meaning it was very responsive and, unlike other GUIs of the time, it did not freeze up when a program was busy.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Windows 95, accompanied by an extensive marketing campaign, was a major success in the marketplace at launch and shortly became the most popular desktop operating system.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In 2007, with the iPhone and later in 2010 with the introduction of the iPad, Apple popularized the post-WIMP style of interaction for multi-touch screens, and those devices were considered to be milestones in the development of mobile devices.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The GUIs familiar to most people as of the mid-late 2010s are Windows, macOS, and the X Window System interfaces for desktop and laptop computers, and Android, Apple's iOS, Symbian, BlackBerry OS, Windows Phone/Windows 10 Mobile, Tizen, WebOS, and Firefox OS for handheld (smartphone) devices.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Since the commands available in command line interfaces can be many, complex operations can be performed using a short sequence of words and symbols.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Custom functions may be used to facilitate access to frequent actions.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Command-line interfaces are more lightweight, as they only recall information necessary for a task; for example, no preview thumbnails or graphical rendering of web pages.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This allows greater efficiency and productivity once many commands are learned.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] But reaching this level takes some time because the command words may not be easily discoverable or mnemonic.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Also, using the command line can become slow and error-prone when users must enter long commands comprising many parameters or several different filenames at once.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] However, *windows, icons, menus, pointer* (WIMP) interfaces present users with many widgets that represent and can trigger some of the system's available commands.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] GUIs can be made quite hard when dialogs are buried deep in a system or moved about to different places during redesigns.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Also, icons and dialog boxes are usually harder for users to script.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] WIMPs extensively use modes, as the meaning of all keys and clicks on specific positions on the screen are redefined all the time.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Command-line interfaces use modes only in limited forms, such as for current directory and environment variables.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Most modern operating systems provide both a GUI and some level of a CLI, although the GUIs usually receive more attention.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] GUI wrappers find a way around the command-line interface versions (CLI) of (typically) Linux and Unix-like software applications and their text-based UIs or typed command labels.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] While command-line or text-based applications allow users to run a program non-interactively, GUI wrappers atop them avoid the steep learning curve of the command-line, which requires commands to be typed on the keyboard.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] By starting a GUI wrapper, users can intuitively interact with, start, stop, and change its working parameters, through graphical icons and visual indicators of a desktop environment, for example.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Applications may also provide both interfaces, and when they do the GUI is usually a WIMP wrapper around the command-line version.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] This is especially common with applications designed for Unix-like operating systems.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The latter used to be implemented first because it allowed the developers to focus exclusively on their product's functionality without bothering about interface details such as designing icons and placing buttons.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Designing programs this way also allows users to run the program in a shell script.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Many environments and games use the methods of 3D graphics to project 3D GUI objects onto the screen.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The use of 3D graphics has become increasingly common in mainstream operating systems (ex.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Windows Aero, and Aqua (macOS)) to create attractive interfaces, termed eye candy (which includes, for example, the use of drop shadows underneath windows and the cursor), or for functional purposes only possible using three dimensions.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] For example, user switching is represented by rotating a cube with faces representing each user's workspace, and window management is represented via a Rolodex-style flipping mechanism in Windows Vista (see Windows Flip 3D).
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In both cases, the operating system transforms windows on-the-fly while continuing to update the content of those windows.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] The GUI is usually WIMP-based, although occasionally other metaphors surface, such as those used in Microsoft Bob, 3dwm, File System Navigator, File System Visualizer, 3D Mailbox, and GopherVR.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Zooming (ZUI) is a related technology that promises to deliver the representation benefits of 3D environments without their usability drawbacks of orientation problems and hidden objects.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] In 2006, Hillcrest Labs introduced the first ZUI for television.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] Augmented reality and virtual reality also make use of 3D GUI elements.
[src:qt-framework/graphical-user-interface] 3D GUIs have appeared in science fiction literature and films, even before certain technologies were feasible or in common use.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:qt-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is currently being developed by The Qt Company, a publicly listed company, and the Qt Project under open-source governance, involving individual developers and organizations working to advance Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is available under both commercial licenses and open-source GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, and LGPL 3.0 licenses.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is used for developing graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and multi-platform applications that run on all major desktop platforms and mobile or embedded platforms.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Most GUI programs created with Qt have a native-looking interface, in which case Qt is classified as a *widget toolkit*.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Non-GUI programs can also be developed, such as command-line tools and consoles for servers.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] An example of such a non-GUI program using Qt is the Cutelyst web framework.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt supports various C++ compilers, including the GCC and Clang C++ compilers and the Visual Studio suite.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] It supports other languages with bindings or extensions, such as Python via Python bindings and PHP via an extension for PHP5, and has extensive internationalization support.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt also provides Qt Quick, that includes a declarative scripting language called QML that allows using JavaScript to provide the logic.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] With Qt Quick, rapid application development for mobile devices became possible, while logic can still be written with native code as well to achieve the best possible performance.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Other features include SQL database access, XML parsing, JSON parsing, thread management and network support.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The latest version of the Qt Framework is Qt 6.11, which was released on 23 March 2026.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Also still supported are versions 6.10 until 7 October 2026 and 6.8 LTS until 8 October 2029.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Version 6.5 LTS is supported for commercial users only until 3 April 2026.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Additionally, extended support for all versions 5.0 (released in 2012) and newer is available for commercial users.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Minor versions of Qt are typically released twice a year and are supported until one year after release date under standard support conditions.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Typically, every third minor version becomes a long-term support version which gets additional patches.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] LTS versions are supported for commercial users until five years after their release date (three years prior to version 6.8).
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In 2017, the Qt Company estimated a community of about 1 million developers worldwide in over 70 industries.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] When first released, Qt used its own paint engine and controls, emulating the look of the different platforms it runs on when it drew its widgets.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This made the porting work easier because very few classes in Qt really depended on the target platform; however, this occasionally led to slight discrepancies where that emulation was imperfect.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Recent versions of Qt use the native style APIs of the different platforms, on platforms that have a native widget set, to query metrics and draw most controls, and do not suffer from such issues as often.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] On some platforms (such as MeeGo and KDE) Qt *is* the native API.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Some other portable graphical toolkits have made different design decisions; for example, wxWidgets uses the toolkits of the target platform for its implementations.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Signals and slots are a language construct introduced in Qt for communication between objects which makes it easy to implement the observer pattern while avoiding boilerplate code.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The concept is that GUI widgets can send signals containing event information which can be received by other controls using special functions known as slots.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The metaobject compiler, termed *moc*, is a tool that is run on the sources of a Qt program.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] It interprets certain macros from the C++ code as annotations, and uses them to generate added C++ code with meta information about the classes used in the program.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This meta information is used by Qt to provide programming features not available natively in C++: signals and slots, introspection and asynchronous function calls.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt moc does not recognise modules in its preprocessor currently.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt can be used in several programming languages other than C++, such as Python, JavaScript, C# and Rust via language bindings; many languages have bindings for Qt 5 and bindings for Qt 4.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In 2025 The Qt Company announced a new "bridging technology" that aimed to re-think the way of interacting with new languages, listing that a proof of concept was being worked on for integrating C#, Rust, Swift, Java/Kotlin, and Python.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Starting with Qt 4.0 the framework was split into individual modules.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] With Qt 5.0 the architecture was modularized even further.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is now split into *essential* and *add-on* modules.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt classes by default do not reside in any namespace, but all classes are prefixed with the letter Q.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt can be configured to be compiled to reside in a user-defined namespace.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is entirely provided through header files, and does not currently support C++ modules.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] There are four editions of Qt available: *Community*, *Indie Mobile*, *Professional* and *Enterprise*.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The Community version is under the open source licenses, while the Indie Mobile, Professional and Enterprise versions, which contain additional functionality and libraries, e.g.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Enterprise Controls are commercially sold by The Qt Company.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] After Nokia opened the Qt source code to the community on Gitorious, various ports appeared.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] There are also some ports of Qt that may be available, but are not supported anymore.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] These platforms are listed in List of platforms supported by Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] See also there for current community support for other lesser known platforms, such as SailfishOS.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt is available under the following free software licenses: GPL 2.0, GPL 3.0, LGPL 3.0 and LGPL 2.1 (with Qt special exception).
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Note that some modules are available only under a GPL license, which means that applications which link to these modules need to comply with that license.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In addition, Qt has always been available under a commercial license, like the Qt Commercial License, that allows developing proprietary applications with no restrictions on licensing.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt comes with its own set of tools to ease cross-platform development, which can otherwise be cumbersome due to different set of development tools.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt Creator is a cross-platform IDE for C++ and QML.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt Designer's GUI layout/design functionality is integrated into the IDE, although Qt Designer can still be started as a standalone tool.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In addition to Qt Creator, Qt provides qmake, a cross-platform build script generation tool that automates the generation of Makefiles for development projects across different platforms.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] There are other tools available in Qt, including the Qt Designer interface builder and the Qt Assistant help browser (which are both embedded in Qt Creator), the Qt Linguist translation tool, uic (user interface compiler), and moc (Meta-Object Compiler).
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In the summer of 1990, Haavard Nord and Eirik Chambe-Eng (the original developers of Qt and the CEO and President, respectively, of The Qt Company) were working together on a database application for ultrasound images written in C++ and running on the classic Mac OS, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] They began development of "Qt" in 1991, three years before the company was incorporated as Quasar Technologies, then changed the name to Troll Tech and then to Trolltech.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The toolkit was called Qt because the letter Q looked appealing in Haavard's Emacs typeface, and "t" was inspired by Xt, the X toolkit.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The first two versions of Qt had only two flavors: Qt/X11 for Unix and Qt/Windows for Windows.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] On 20 May 1995 Trolltech publicly released Qt 0.90 for X11/Linux with the source code under the *Qt Free Edition License*.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This license was viewed as not compliant with the free software definition by Free Software Foundation because, while the source was available, it did not allow the redistribution of modified versions.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Trolltech used this license until version 1.45.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Controversy erupted around 1998 when it became clear that the K Desktop Environment was going to become one of the leading desktop environments for Linux.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] As it was based on Qt, many people in the free software movement worried that an essential piece of one of their major operating systems would be proprietary.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The Windows platform was available only under a proprietary license, which meant free/open source applications written in Qt for X11 could not be ported to Windows without purchasing the proprietary edition.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] With the release of version 2.0 of the toolkit in mid-1999, the license was changed to the Q Public License (QPL), a free software license, but one regarded by the Free Software Foundation as incompatible with the GPL.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Compromises were sought between KDE and Trolltech whereby Qt would not be able to fall under a more restrictive license than the QPL, even if Trolltech was bought out or went bankrupt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This led to the creation of the KDE Free Qt foundation, which guarantees that Qt would fall under a BSD-style license should no free/open source version of Qt be released during 12 months.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In 2000, Qt/X11 2.2 was released under the GPL v2, ending all controversy regarding GPL compatibility.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] At the end of 2001, Trolltech released Qt 3.0, which added support for Mac OS X (now known as macOS).
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The Mac OS X support was available only in the proprietary license until June 2003, when Trolltech released Qt 3.2 with Mac OS X support available under the GPL.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In 2002, members of the KDE on Cygwin project began porting the GPL licensed Qt/X11 code base to Windows.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This was in response to Trolltech's refusal to license Qt/Windows under the GPL on the grounds that Windows was not a free/open source software platform.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The project achieved some success although it never reached production quality.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This was resolved when Trolltech released Qt 4.0 also for Windows under the GPL in June 2005.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt 4 supported the same set of platforms in the free software/open source editions as in the proprietary edition, so it is possible, with Qt 4.0 and later releases, to create GPL-licensed free/open source applications using Qt on all supported platforms.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The GPL v3 with special exception was later added as an added licensing option.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The GPL exception allows the final application to be licensed under various GPL-incompatible free software/open source licenses such as the Mozilla Public License 1.1.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Nokia acquired Trolltech ASA on 17 June 2008 and changed the name first to Qt Software, then to Qt Development Frameworks.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Nokia focused on turning Qt into the main development platform for its devices, including a port to the Symbian S60 platform.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Version 1.0 of the Nokia Qt SDK was released on 23 June 2010.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The source code was made available over Gitorious, a community oriented git source code repository, with a goal of creating a broader community using and improving Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] On 14 January 2009, Qt version 4.5 added another option, the LGPL, to make Qt more attractive for both non-GPL open source projects and closed applications.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In February 2011, Nokia announced its decision to discontinue Symbian technologies and base their future smartphones on the Windows Phone platform instead (and since then support for that platform has also been dropped).
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In March 2011, Nokia sold the commercial licensing part of Qt to Digia, creating Qt Commercial.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In August 2012, Digia announced that it would acquire Qt from Nokia.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The Qt team at Digia started their work in September 2012.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] They released Qt 5.0 within a month and newer versions every six months with new features and additional supported platforms.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In September 2014, Digia transferred the Qt business and copyrights to their wholly owned subsidiary, The Qt Company, which owns 25 brands related to Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] In May 2016, Digia and Qt demerged completely into two independent companies.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt 5 was officially released on 19 December 2012.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] This new version marked a major change in the platform, with hardware-accelerated graphics, QML and JavaScript playing a major role.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] The traditional C++-only QWidgets continued to be supported, but did not benefit from the performance improvements available through the new architecture.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Qt 5 brings significant improvements to the speed and ease of developing user interfaces.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Framework development of Qt 5 moved to open governance at qt-project.org, which made it possible for developers outside Digia to submit patches for review.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Aside from The Qt Company, many organizations and individuals using Qt as their development platform participate in the open development of Qt via the Qt Project.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] One such Qt contributor is Klarälvdalens Datakonsult AB, a Swedish Qt consulting company.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] KDAB is involved in many areas, including maintenance of several components.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Together with RIM/BlackBerry, KDAB is maintaining the QNX and BlackBerry 10 ports of Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] Another participator is Intel, contributing for example Wayland support.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] AudioCodes maintains IBM ClearCase support in Qt Creator.
[src:qt-framework/qt-software] As a heavy user of Qt, the KDE project submits many patches and features from its developer library KDE Frameworks back to Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The Qt Widgets Module provides a set of UI elements to create classic desktop-style user interfaces.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] See the User Interfaces overview for more information on using widgets.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Widgets are the primary elements for creating user interfaces in Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Widgets can display data and status information, receive user input, and provide a container for other widgets that should be grouped together.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] A widget that is not embedded in a parent widget is called a window.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The QWidget class provides the basic capability to render to the screen and to handle user input events.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] All UI elements that Qt provides are either subclasses of QWidget or are used in connection with a QWidget subclass.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] To create custom widgets, subclass QWidget or a suitable subclass and reimplement the virtual event handlers.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Styles draw on behalf of widgets and encapsulate the look and feel of a GUI.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Qt's built-in widgets use the QStyle class to perform nearly all of their drawing, ensuring that they look exactly like the equivalent native widgets.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Qt Style Sheets are a powerful mechanism that lets you customize the appearance of widgets, in addition to what is already possible by subclassing QStyle.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Layouts are an elegant and flexible way to automatically arrange child widgets within their container.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Each widget reports its size requirements to the layout through the sizeHint and sizePolicy properties, and the layout distributes the available space accordingly.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Qt Widgets Designer is a powerful tool for interactively creating and arranging widgets in layouts.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The model/view architecture provides classes that manage the way data is presented to the user.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Data-driven applications which use lists and tables are structured to separate the data and view using models, views, and delegates.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The Graphics View Framework is for managing and interacting with a large number of custom-made 2D graphical items, and a view widget for visualizing the items, with support for zooming and rotation.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Using a Qt module's C++ API requires linking against the module library, either directly or through other dependencies.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Several build tools have dedicated support for this, including CMake and qmake.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] For more details, see the Build with CMake overview.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Changes to Qt Widgets lists important changes in the module API and functionality that were done for the Qt 6 series of Qt.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The Qt Widgets module is available under commercial licenses from The Qt Company.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] In addition, it is available under free software licenses: The GNU Lesser General Public License, version 3, or the GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Documentation contributions included herein are the copyrights of their respective owners.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] The documentation provided herein is licensed under the terms of the GNU Free Documentation License version 1.3 as published by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] Qt and respective logos are trademarks of The Qt Company Ltd. in Finland and/or other countries worldwide.
[src:qt-framework/qtwidgets-index] All other trademarks are property of their respective owners.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] The signal/slot system fits well with the way graphical user interfaces are designed.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] Similarly, the signal/slot system can be used for other non-GUI usages, for example asynchronous I/O (including sockets, pipes, serial devices, etc.) event notification or to associate timeout events with appropriate object instances and methods or functions.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] It is easy to use and no registration/deregistration/invocation code need to be written, because Qt's metaobject compiler (MOC) automatically generates the needed infrastructure.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] A spreadsheet programs update system could be implemented using signals and slots such that when a cell is changed, its dependent cells are notified/updated.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] There are some implementations of signal/slot systems based on C++ templates, which don't require the extra metaobject compiler, as used by Qt, such as libsigc++, sigslot, vdk-signals, nano-signal-slot, neosigslot, Signals, boost.signals2, Synapse, Cpp::Events, Platinum, JBroadcaster and KDBindings.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) languages such as C# also supports a similar construct although with a different terminology and syntax: events play the role of signals, and delegates are the slots.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] Another implementation of signals exists for ActionScript 3.0, inspired by C# events and signals/slots in Qt.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] Additionally, a delegate can be a local variable, much like a function pointer, while a slot in Qt must be a class member declared as such.
[src:qt-framework/signals-and-slots] The C based GObject system also provides similar functionality via GSignal.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:qt-framework/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:qt-framework/widget-gui] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
